My Monoprice filament spools are about 2mm wider than the short axis bars, which caused them to rub the uprights and not spin freely. The I widened the distance between the uprights to 84mm, which allows me to mount 2 spools on the side of the printer.
I also made the axis bar one piece, to remove the 6mm overlap caused by using two short axis bars.
The uprights are slightly bowed at the hook end attaching to the printer, because the top cutout of my printer is slightly smaller, but I find the bowing helps keep the whole unit from shaking all over. I ended up making the filament guide out of an axis bar, and the feed hole section was pulled from FunkyArt's filament guide. I noticed my filament was binding on the small hole, so I drilled out the feed hole and used small section of my filament tube to smooth the feed.

comments.text: You place the tool on the build surface and lower the extruder nozzle into the round hole on the tool.  Don't lower it too much so it will be jammed against the build surface. title: Blood Cells: a Visual funny Kit for Biology

description.text:
This kit is composed by three models (.obj and .stl) to show a general overview in terms of shape and morphology of blood cells. Models for leukocyte, erythrocyte and thrombocyte have been modelled and shown in the file section.
I think that blood cells are very important in the study of biology, since they are involved in many vital processes such as coagulation, immune response and carrying of oxygen in the body. 
These models are not perfect, but they can be used as an aid discuss their functionality in a more-visible way in classrooms. Scaling the models is possible and, in addition, can help to show the difference in terms of dimensions between these three cells.

Notes: I didn't print them so, unfortunately, I cannot suggest any parameters to follow.
However, I would be very happy if someone will suggest me any modification and/or improvement in order to ensure a good printability of them.
I designed the models and then did the rendering with the software Sculptris.

title: Dial Indicator Mount for Wanhao Duplicator i3 / Prusa

description.text:
Wanted a different way to level my bed so I ordered an inexpensive dial indicator and then designed this mount for it in Solidworks. It's designed to be tensioned in place with m6 bolts and nuts. You can place a bolt in all three holes if you'd like or just tighten one through the dial indicator hole tightly. Each bolt hole can be used as a position for the indicator. I am using the middle one as my indicator is relatively short. Designed it to be printed without supports, and I used PETG for strength. This clips on your rods that vertical of eachother. This is my project of a functions drawer (or stencil). The idea came out trying to teach students the sine and cosine waves' Theory, having a handy and portable object which allows them to draw a correct wave form with its own unit circle.

For all my designs, I’ve always used the 2D/3D software AutoCAD student edition, for this one precisely the 2016 version. AutoCAD doesn’t implement a native tool for creating functions, so I downloaded an external free one (that’s actually very simple to use, even for beginners) called AutoLISP. FIRST VERSION (mechanical pencil 1mm) You must use a mechanical pencil with 1mm of lead diameter. From 2D To 3D FINAL VERSION (mechanical pencil 0.5mm) You must use a mechanical pencil with 0.5mm of lead diameter. From 2D To 3D

Objectives • Study and learn functions theory;
• Introduce students to 3D software (AutoCAD and others);
• Make students aware about the differences between Sinusoidal and Cosinusoidal waves;
• Learn how to draw functions;
• Study of the Unit Circle and its different degrees. Source: Wikipedia Audience • All the students that are attending a secondary school (IT and Electronic classes);
• Each class allowed to use PCs (get start with 3D software);
• Each class allowed to use Electronic labs (such as utilizing oscilloscopes or multimeters...);
• Each person who wants to start the study of trigonometric functions (who is already studying it either);
• Teachers can use it to improve their teaching system. Preparation • Students will need PCs with AutoCAD installed;
• Students should have some knowledge about 2D drawing (but also beginners will learn to use it);
• A teacher will follow and lead the students on modelling the object, and help them with 3D printer software and hardware;
• Students should make a report about actions they've needed to take to get the result;
• The teacher must document all the steps taken by the students and write down each student's improvement;
• Students will need a mechanical pencil with lead of 0.5mm to use it;
• At the end students can start or continue with theory, making the realized objects useful. Lead 0.5mm Students at Work They will have to choose sinusoidal waves with different periods and amplitudes (using whichever 3D program they want). As I said, I used Autocad so I'm going to introduce you to which field you must consider:
  • Period;
  • Amplitude (pp stands for peak-to-peak);
  • Number of cycles (how many times a period is repeated );
    • After choosing the period and amplitude values, and the number of cycles though, they can create as many different waves they want. period and amplitude doubled After the waves have been created, students can make a forward step offsetting, creating edges and extruding the whole draw. (like the following image) Steps
  • Study Sine and Cosine trigonometric functions;
  • Learn how to use a 2D/3D software, such as AutoCAD;
  • Design the object helping yourself with the AutoLISP tool;
  • Send it to the 3D printer;
  • Make your observations about the result;
  • Start with using it for personal and educational purposes;
    • Results At the end of this experience, each student should have learnt:
    • Trigonometric functions theory;
    • Basics of 2D/3D modelling;
    • 3D printer settings and materials; Once students have reported every single step they made, the experiment is finished. Rendered Stencils How I Printed it Rostock Mini in action Final Product

title: modular tool-holder rack for MakerBot Cupcake

description.text:
There's been a few tool-holders posted, but they never fit my set of tools.   So I thought, why not make a modular tool rack that hangs off the side of the Cupcake and that people can customize.
There are two basic pieces -- "lip" and "nolip".  The nolip pieces are for lighter objects and fit next the the z-axis parts and rely upon the lip pieces for support.  The lip pieces are for heavier parts and clip onto the side of the makerbot.
Due to the space between the z-bolts not being a multiple of the z-bolt mounts, there will be a small gap.  If this really, really bothers you, stretch out one of your lip pieces to take up the slack.

These are printed on a well-tuned Cupcake using a Mk6 Stepstruder and the snap dimensions are rather tight.  If you have an older extruder, you will probably need to tweak the size of the snap components and possibly the lip.
I've included two "blank" pieces to make it easier to create your own tool inserts.

description.text: This is a stand to hold a Dwyer Rate-Master Polycarbonate Flowmeter (Model A) upright on a desk surface. Dwyer expects you to mount these to vertical surfaces, but if you are doing some basic testing with temporary set ups, you don't want to have to mount it. The flow meter just fits in the U-shaped slot. It could be glued in place for more security.

A while ago I came up with a design for a new X axis for a Vertical configuration (vX config) based on bar spacing of 70mm for the vertical spacing and 30mm between the Z axis lead screw and smooth rod, per the original Reprap Mendel spec. Long story short, my printer is running great now after some time of neglect and I've been able to work on this design more and iron out some potential kinks! The key difference now is that in addition to a Vertical configuration, I've come up with a Horizontal configuration (hX config) which uses the same zClamps, so if you're perfectly happy with your carriage and extruder, but want to try new Z ends this should offer an alternative to the default Mendel setup. As for the vX config, it's untested in the sense that I don't have a working setup with this implementation but I will eventually. For now I have printed all parts except the main motor bracket and all prints have gone well and Slicr is doing a good job bridging the overhangs without using support. Currently I'm testing out the Horizontal configuration and will update with any notes. .
Just for the sake of clarity, the Configurations break down like this: vX Config
  • zClamp_4off
  • vX_motorBracket_1off
  • vX_barClamp_4off
    • hX Config
  • zClamp 4off
  • hX_motorBracketA_1off
  • hX_motorBracketB_1off
  • hX_endBracketA_1off
  • hX_endBracketB_1off
  • hX_barClamp_4off

Materials
I'll fill this out once I have a proper list of the bolts needed but for now, experienced modders should be able to piece it together in the mean time :) . Z Clamp Assembly (universal):
1) Install linear bearings and M8 nut on Z axis rods
2) Align linear bearings and M8 nut with one half of Z clamp and close with other half of the Z clamp
3) Insert M4 bolt into center hole with 2 M4 washers and nut (if assembling vX config, install motor bracket first, then fasteners) vX Assembly:
1) Install vX_motorBracket when installing left side zClamps using M4 bolt, M4 washers and nut
2) Insert M4 bolt withM4 washer into a remaining hole, then place vX_barClamp, M4 washer, small bearing, M4 washer, M5 Mud washer and finally an M4 nut but leave them loose
3) Repeat for each remaining corner
4) Insert X axis smooth rods into clamps and tighten down all corners hX Assembly:
1) Place endBrackets A and B on the correct sides of the installed Z clamp assembly and fit M4 bolt with 2 M4 washers and a nut
2) Install small bearings on endBracketA and B with 3 M4 washers, M5 Mud Washer and nut each
3) Repeat Steps 1 and 2 for motorBracketA and B, as well as bearings.
4) Install motor to motorBrackets using M3 bolts Notes:
  • before tightening down the X axis smooth rod clamps for either config, it's probably a good idea to slide your X carriage all the way to that side, tighten clamps then slide to the other side and tighten the other clamps
    • For now I'll be focusing on the hX config because I want to make my own extruder/carriage for the vX config based on Gregg's Accessible extruder, or something close to that, so in the mean time I'll make sure the hX works well before moving onto the vX, but it should work fine. Be sure to leave a comment with any questions or suggestions!
